{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584408"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:45:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:45:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14515"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14515"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.13,0.46,0.12,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115536"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7210"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97539"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"3733"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45137"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115536"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChromosomal translocations are important genetic alterations in haematological malignancies. Many B-cell lymphomas arise from errors during immunoglobulin gene rearrangement, resulting in specific translocations that juxtapose oncogenes with immunoglobulin regulatory elements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn mantle cell lymphoma, a specific translocation leads to overexpression of a cell cycle regulatory protein that promotes progression from G1 to S phase.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following chromosomal translocations is seen in this type of lymphoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["t(8;14)","t(9;22)","t(11;14)","t(14;18)","t(15;17)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Et(11;14)\u003C/strong\u003E translocation is the correct answer. This translocation juxtaposes the cyclin D1 gene (CCND1) located on chromosome 11q13 with the immunoglobulin heavy chain (IGH) gene enhancer on chromosome 14q32. The powerful IGH enhancer drives constitutive overexpression of cyclin D1, a key regulator of the G1/S cell cycle checkpoint. This overexpression promotes uncontrolled cell proliferation characteristic of mantle cell lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Et(8;14)\u003C/strong\u003E translocation occurs in Burkitt lymphoma and involves the MYC oncogene on chromosome 8 and the IGH gene on chromosome 14, resulting in MYC overexpression rather than cyclin D1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Et(9;22)\u003C/strong\u003E translocation creates the Philadelphia chromosome found in chronic myeloid leukaemia. It produces the BCR::ABL1 fusion protein with constitutive tyrosine kinase activity, not affecting cyclin D1 expression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Et(14;18)\u003C/strong\u003E translocation is characteristic of follicular lymphoma. It places the BCL2 anti-apoptotic gene under control of the IGH enhancer, leading to BCL2 overexpression and inhibition of apoptosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Et(15;17)\u003C/strong\u003E translocation is specific to acute promyelocytic leukaemia and creates the PML::RARA fusion gene, which blocks myeloid differentiation at the promyelocyte stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese translocations commonly involve immunoglobulin genes because B cells undergo programmed DNA double-strand breaks during V(D)J recombination and class switch recombination, creating opportunities for aberrant chromosomal rearrangements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The t(11;14) translocation juxtaposes the cyclin D1 gene on chromosome 11 with the immunoglobulin heavy chain gene on chromosome 14.","Cyclin D1 overexpression results from the t(11;14) translocation and drives uncontrolled cell cycle progression in mantle cell lymphoma.","Chromosomal translocations involving immunoglobulin genes are common in B-cell malignancies due to errors during V(D)J recombination."],"references":["Armitage JO, Longo DL. Mantle-Cell Lymphoma. N Engl J Med. 2022;386(26):2495-2506. doi:10.1056/NEJMra2202672","Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020; Chapter 13; pages 602-603."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97539"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14515"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97539"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T11:38:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T11:38:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7210"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115536"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3733"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Mantle cell lymphoma","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-09-23T21:59:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T21:59:37+09:30"},